1,1852	african orphan boy african orphan boy far away one valleys south africa there lived heathen family they were rich flocks herds many years they sowed ground gathered fruits peace some distance family dwelt warlike tribe called zoolahs which often formed into bands invaded country road these attacks they used first kill men then they carried off cattle broke down huts set fire cornfields one day these savage men rushed into valley where african family lived they slew father left mother her little son mossetse side ruins their hut widow her child sat down weep their home gone their best earthly friend slain all they had world torn them their wicked foes poor heathen woman knew not god saw her her child saw hagar ishmael desert nor did know father fatherless husband widow no gospel had ever reached her dark mind nor had been taught bend her knees prayer widow took sharp stick too ill seek food gave her little boy sent him dig up roots collect kind grass which time ripe grass so hard coarse even cattle would scarcely eat but yielded few handfuls grain ground between two stones formed into grassbread soon health poor widow began fail weeks passed away no one came their help her sadness thought who would provide her little boy when dead used little strength had make large quantity grassbread might have supply if grew worse her orphan child if were taken him death some days after had made supply food lay ruins her hut unable move old skin her only covering when cold shiverings fever came over her mossetse still too young know mothers danger said himself why does not my mother sit me bright beams sun used do one day called him feeble voice my child go some one finding thee will have pity thee take thee up leave me am nearly dead two days thou hast not eaten any thing follow yon footpath which crosses valley some one will surely meet thee little mossetse afraid said dying mother do not speak so makes me cry no you will soon well shall no longer hungry while again spoke him died but knew not distress crept under old skin covered mother three days passed away wondered why slept so long called her but made no answer distress went sat down door hut when african woman passing stopped look lonely child went into hut then told mossetse mother dead dead did not know what meant but when made understand mother would not speak move again sorrow filled young heart while woman coldly turned away left him alone misery all night sat desert side dead body mother when morning came thought would go along narrow path which spoke walked some hours when came place where native work mossetse sat down little way off though spoke not word man looked him seeing faint tired covered dust drew near then offered take little wanderer stream water wash refresh limbs sight water boy cried aloud oh do not drown me will your servant can take care your kids calm distress kind stranger called own children play him while hastened fetch some bread milk when brought poor orphan had been so long without either eating drinking first draught milk caused him utter cry had scarcely power eat bread little time however gained strength became one family kind protector but sorrows orphan had not come end savage invaders now threatened attack place where had found new home fosterfather saw they must all hasten away told mossetse flee huts some chiefs who were able protect provide him love you my own child said kind man but go have done you all my power do then tied some food around orphan boys neck hastened secure own family flight child now sat down roadside shed tears thought forsaken all while thus weeping troop savage men rushed along road they soon overtook mossetses kind benefactor killed him all family next morning all remained them were few scattered bones savages had not only killed them but had feasted their bodies if mossetse had been them would have been slain eaten too night came poor boy crept under bush when morning dawned came forth not knowing what do whither go walked till came mountain mountain found cave opening side here made dreary home how sad desolate now state sheepskin worn torn cave dwelling wild berries roots were food night rest broken fierce howlings wild beasts no fire no covering no friend no companion possessed poor little mossetse week after week month after month passed away until had lived cave more than year want length forced him leave mountain cave set out not knowing whither went but after walking many weary miles came huts some africans who received him friendly way among them took up abode mossetse grew up like rest heathen sin ignorance without god world without hope world come years passed away last some missionaries came spot one occasion when missionary showing god preserver men mossetse rose ground said true heavenly father whom now learn watched over me directed my steps gave me kind friend who fed me preserved me death my cave mountains what have done god who loved me so much why has not permitted me perish am ear corn left standing midst field stricken hail not companion children who were killed did not sleep them beneath same cloak not have slept them again night which they perished live miracle god said mossetse shall live live know him who caused me live time wish can no others day ceased live heathen after sincerity had been proved three years publicly admitted church says missionary finest scene have beheld africa placed midst many hundreds natives presence chief tribe eyes beaming joy thus spoke what love jesus mossetse indeed true thou art christian smallest worm among worms called men how hast thou been remembered god see nothing good me all has been spoiled my ingratitude my sins have nailed saviour cross renounce world joy have taken my shield see stand ready combat jesus who has loved me so much now shall my king my sole good my portion spoke all who stood around listened surprise words mossetse received name moses baptism which name took remind him deliverances god had wrought behalf few days after missionary asked him if did not sometimes wish run ways sin do not know said how man who had received stab breast sword should desire wounded second time have suffered too much agony my conscience seek renew find peace which enjoy far greater value than vanities which have had give up little orphan children who read account should take comfort encouraged they may say king david when my father my mother forsake me then lord will take me up same god who watched over orphan boy heathen africa has preserved them if they put their trust him will their father friend all their days earth if like mossetse they repent sin believe jesus their saviour they shall ever dwell him heaven little account also shows value christian missions african orphan would not have known who had saved him all dangers if missionaries had not been sent preach gospel land sin would have lived without hope would have died but heard jesus holy spirit blessed soul what heard happy mossetse may many more your sable brethren brought love saviour sinners may those children christian lands who help send gospel heathen learn know value gospel themselves
2,1857	african woman child praying her bedside lucile clarke memorial childrens library african woman littlemary sitting window her mother saw poor old african woman go omother said do not love woman all why not mary because black do not like anybody black her mother said mary mary am sorry hear you talk so foolish wicked mary looked very sober then said why wicked mother my dear wrong because god has told us love everybody world god made poor woman well you will call her see you mary frightened said no mother if you please do not call her yes my dear wish teach you lesson then raised window asked old woman come marys mother said good woman what do you think little girl dear little miss madam may give her peace then took peach out her basket gave mary little girl felt very much ashamed hung down her head old woman then said once had three little girls but they are all dead lord knows what best tears came into her eyes mary ready weep too then mrs ewing gave woman some work do knew her very well after woman had gone mary said mother am sorry being so foolish naughty will not hate black people any more her mother said my dear you should not hate any gods creatures all men women are made one blood all are brethren poor african woman brought america when young now old very poor besides pious woman am sure christ lovesher you ought love her too do her all good you can mary said nothing but after all felt some dislike poor patty not long after mary very sick bed several weeks one morning old african woman knocked door said mrs ewing where little miss mary never see her going school then mrs ewing took her into chamber where marylay sick old patty very sorry came nursed mary seven days nights when little girl got well said mother will never hate anybody again having dark skin poor patty great deal better than am end american sundayschool union no chestnut street philadelphia have published more than varieties books maps cards cand over library bookson good paper type numerousplates engravings american sundayschool union chestnut st philadelphia broadway new york
